## Solution: Use `@added` decorator

You cannot use `@added` directly on a spread (`...`), but you can avoid the spread and manually add the property with the versioning decorator.

### Instead of spreading:

```typespec
// ❌ This applies to ALL versions
model MyResourceProperties {
  ...ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}
```

### Add the property explicitly with `@added`:

```typespec
import "@azure-tools/typespec-azure-resource-manager";

using Azure.ResourceManager;
using TypeSpec.Versioning;

model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  // ...

  @added(Versions.v2025_05_04_preview)
  ...ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}
```

**Key point:** The `@added` decorator can be placed directly before the spread statement (`...`) at the model level where it's used — typically on the **resource model itself**, not the properties model.

If the spread is inside a nested properties model and `@added` on the spread doesn't compile, explicitly declare the property instead:

```typespec
model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  @added(Versions.v2025_05_04_preview)
  identity?: ManagedServiceIdentity;
}
```

This ensures `identity` only appears in `2025-05-04-preview` and later, leaving prior API versions unchanged.

Make sure `v2025_05_04_preview` is defined in your `Versions` enum:

```typespec
enum Versions {
  v2024_01_01: "2024-01-01",
  v2025_05_04_preview: "2025-05-04-preview",
}
```

